<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="type locality">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Intertidal, south coast of Hainan, China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Small (L to 10 mm), sub-circular, longer than high, posteriorly slightly truncate, moderately inflated. Shell white, slightly translucent and waxy in appearance. Sculpture of many, fine, low, commarginal lamellae and low radial ribs which are broader and more prominent towards the anterior and posterior. Radial ribs are conspicuously fluted where commarginal lamellae cross giving a crinkled appearance. Lunule elongate, lanceolate and impressed, slightly asymmetrical. Ligament internal, short, situated on a broadly triangular resilifer. Hinge: right valve with single, cardinal tooth, anterior and posterior lateral teeth small, posterior tooth elongate. Left valve with two narrow cardinal teeth, a small anterior lateral socket and posterior lateral narrow socket. Anterior adductor muscle scar medium-long, detached for ca. 50 % of length. Posterior scar ovate. Pallial line entire, sometimes partially discontinuous or irregularly lobate. Shell margin crenulate, with crenulations coarser towards anterior and posterior.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Singapore</emphasis>
: Pulau Semakau (NHMUK), Seringat Bay (NHMUK). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Malaysia</emphasis>
: Langkawi (AMS). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Western Thailand</emphasis>
: Ao Bang Ben, Kapoe (NHMUK), Ban Bang Ben (NHMUK), Tung Nam Dan, Phang Nga Province (NHMUK), 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Eastern Thailand</emphasis>
: Kungkraben Bay (NHMUK). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Cambodia</emphasis>
: 5 km E of port, Sihanoukville (NHMUK). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Vietnam</emphasis>
: Dam Bay near Nha Trang (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/13235818.2019.1638567" author="Zvonareva, SS" journalOrPublisher="Molluscan Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="296 - 312" refId="B57" refString="Zvonareva, SS, Mekhova, ES, Ha Vo, T, Kantor, YI, 2019. Checklist of bivalve molluscs in mangroves of Khanh Hoa Province, Vietnam. Molluscan Research 39: 296 - 312" title="Checklist of bivalve molluscs in mangroves of Khanh Hoa Province, Vietnam." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/13235818.2019.1638567" volume="39" year="2019">Zvonareva et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">China</emphasis>
: Hainan (MNHN), Hong Kong (NHMUK), Daya Bay (NHMUK).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Intertidal to shallow sub-tidal seagrass and muddy habitats. Recorded at high densities in muddy seagrass and mangrove fringe habitats of eastern and western Thailand (
<bibRefCitation author="Meyer, E" journalOrPublisher="Raffles Museum Bulletin of Zoology, supplement" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="41 - 55" refId="B33" refString="Meyer, E, Nilkerd, B, Glover, EA, Taylor, JD, 2008. Ecological importance of chemoautotrophic lucinid bivalves in a peri-mangrove community in Eastern Thailand. Raffles Museum Bulletin of Zoology, supplement 18: 41 - 55" title="Ecological importance of chemoautotrophic lucinid bivalves in a peri-mangrove community in Eastern Thailand." volume="18" year="2008">Meyer et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; Rattanachot and Prathep 2016). Gill structure and symbiotic bacteria are illustrated in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Rugalucina vietnamica (Zorina, 1978). A-C Pillucina vietnamica Zorina, 1978 syntypes (ZISP), exterior of right valve and interior of left and right valves, Hainan, China, L 5.5 - 8.9 mm D internal drawing of C. E, F R. vietnamica Palau Semaku, Singapore (NHMUK 20150057), L 8.5 mm G-L R. vietnamica Kungkraben Bay, eastern Thailand (NHMUK 20191072) G exterior of right valve, L 7.0 mm. H exterior of left valve, L 7.0 mm I, J interior of left and right valves, L 7.7 mm K dorsal view L 5.6 mm L, M detail of hinge of I and J. N Section through gill of Rugalucina vietnamica Kungkraben Bay, Thailand showing filaments with ciliary (cz) and bacteriocyte zones (bz). Critical-point dried preparation O detail showing abundant bacterial symbionts in bacteriocytes. Scale bars: 20 µm (N); 10 µm (O)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.899.47070.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/364611" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.899.47070.figure4">Fig. 4N, O</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="109" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="109">
Although we formerly recorded 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Lucinidae" genus="Rugalucina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rugalucina vietnamica" order="Lucinida" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vietnamica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">Rugalucina vietnamica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a broad longitudinal range from the northern Red Sea to southern China (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3853/j.0067-1975.53.2001.1349" author="Glover, EA" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Australian Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="263 - 292" refId="B18" refString="Glover, EA, Taylor, JD, 2001. Systematic revision of Australian and Indo-Pacific Lucinidae (Mollusca: Bivalvia): Pillucina, Wallucina and descriptions of two new genera and four new species. Records of the Australian Museum 53: 263 - 292" title="Systematic revision of Australian and Indo-Pacific Lucinidae (Mollusca: Bivalvia): Pillucina, Wallucina and descriptions of two new genera and four new species." url="https://doi.org/10.3853/j.0067-1975.53.2001.1349" volume="53" year="2001">Glover and Taylor 2001</bibRefCitation>
) we now regard it as having a narrower range along the continental margin of south eastern Asia with few records from islands. Despite intensive sampling by the MNHN Paris Expeditions around Panglao, Philippines (2004, 2005) and Papua New Guinea (2012, 2014) no 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. vietnamica" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" rank="species" species="vietnamica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="109">R. vietnamica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Glover, EA" editor="Heros, V" journalOrPublisher="Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle" pageId="0" pageNumber="109" pagination="865 - 234" refId="B20" refString="Glover, EA, Taylor, JD, 2016. Lucinidae of the Philippines: highest known diversity and ubiquity of chemosymbiotic bivalves from intertidal to bathyal depths (Mollusca: Bivalvia). In: Heros, V, Strong, E, Bouchet, P, Eds., Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos, volume 29. . Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle 20: 865 - 234" title="Lucinidae of the Philippines: highest known diversity and ubiquity of chemosymbiotic bivalves from intertidal to bathyal depths (Mollusca: Bivalvia)." volume="20" volumeTitle="Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos, volume 29." year="2016">Glover and Taylor 2016</bibRefCitation>
and unpublished data).
</paragraph>
